data.details:
She’s a Park Explorer at Paynes Prairie Preserve State Park- DBJ
Grades: K, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5

Paynes Prairie is home to a great diversity of plants and animals, including alligators, bison, horses, and more than 270 species of birds.  As a wetland, it also plays a critical role in cleaning and protecting our drinking water.  Millions of gallons of water per day flow into the 16,000-acre prairie basin, and eventually into the Alachua Sink – an important feature of Paynes Prairie.  Come explore Sweetwater Wetlands Park and experience the “open range” of the Prairie.  Help rangers determine the quality of water in different habitats and learn about our watershed, the Floridan Aquifer, and what you can do to help keep water clean and wetland habitats healthy.  Fun patch provided. Park entrance fee included.

*This event is for 2016 registered Girl Scouts, and registered & approved adult volunteers.
* For safety and supervision reasons, troops and individuals are not permitted to bring non-Girl Scouts or siblings. 
*Girl/adult ratios must be followed and adults are expected to stay on the premises during the event. 

$8/girl, $8/adult
Contact: Brittany McCallister 904.389.3071
